          "title": "The day of small things and the eyes that see everything",
          "body": "Verse 10 contains one of the most pastorally pointed questions in prophetic literature: 'Who has despised the day of small things?' The question does not ask whether anyone has despised it — the prophetic rebuke assumes they have. Ezra 3:12 records that the old men who had seen Solomon's temple wept at the new foundation because it looked so small. Haggai 2:3 records the same painful comparison: 'Who is left among you who saw this house in its former glory? And how do you see it now? Does it not seem to you like nothing in comparison?' Against this despair, God plants two realities in the same verse. First, the seven eyes of the LORD — the same seven lamps on the lampstand — are not passive decoration but active omniscient surveillance ranging 'to and fro throughout the earth' (4:10; cf. 2 Chronicles 16:9). God sees the plumb line in Zerubbabel's hand not as a disappointing symbol of small-scale work but as the very object that makes His eyes glad. Second, the promise: 'these seven will be glad when they see the plumb line in the hand of Zerubbabel.' Divine rejoicing over small, faithful obedience is the chapter's most counterintuitive claim."
